00:11:56,120 --> 00:11:58,520
 Neither shall you touch it lest you die.

264
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:00,540
 And so two things we see in Eve's response

265
00:12:00,540 --> 00:12:02,480
 that are a little curious is that

266
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:04,120
 when you look at the previous chapter,

267
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:06,240
 God never said they couldn't touch the fruit

268
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:07,440
 or touch the tree.

269
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:10,040
 Somehow Adam and Eve, I don't know if they misheard

270
00:12:10,040 --> 00:12:12,240
 or added it maybe for their own protection,

271
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:15,040
 but they added something to what God had said.

272
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:18,280
 What's more, we see that Satan,

273
00:12:18,280 --> 00:12:21,280
 and this is, I believe, still one of his tactics today.

274
00:12:21,280 --> 00:12:22,880
 He flips what God says.

275
00:12:22,880 --> 00:12:27,100
 And so when we see God spoke to Adam that all the trees,

276
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:30,160
 all the fruit you can eat from, but not this one.

277
00:12:30,160 --> 00:12:34,380
 What Satan does is he minimizes what God has given Adam

278
00:12:34,380 --> 00:12:36,320
 and he maximizes that restriction.

279
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:40,040
 It says, did God say you couldn't eat from any tree?

280
00:12:40,040 --> 00:12:42,740
 And so what Satan does is he wants the woman

281
00:12:42,740 --> 00:12:46,080
 and the man to focus on the one thing God said

282
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:48,340
 wasn't for them that they shouldn't have.

283
00:12:48,340 --> 00:12:51,820
 Instead of focusing on all that God had given them,

284
00:12:51,820 --> 00:12:53,620
 I'm somebody who loves fruit.

285
00:12:53,620 --> 00:12:55,740
 You can ask my wife, you can ask Rachel.

286
00:12:55,740 --> 00:12:58,020
 I love fruit, I'm always looking for new fruit.

287
00:12:58,020 --> 00:13:00,160
 There's so many fruit in the world,

288
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:02,460
 and they had all of it, and I can't believe it.

289
00:13:02,460 --> 00:13:04,820
 They allow the devil to tempt them to only focus

290
00:13:04,820 --> 00:13:07,060
 on that one tree they couldn't have.

291
00:13:07,060 --> 00:13:10,180
 But as much as I have a hard time understanding

292
00:13:10,180 --> 00:13:12,820
 why they would do that, we do the same thing.

293
00:13:12,820 --> 00:13:16,540
 God has given us so much goodness in the world,

294
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:20,180
 and yet we're often tempted to focus on those things

295
00:13:20,180 --> 00:13:23,400
 that we can't have because there's something in human pride

296
00:13:23,400 --> 00:13:26,460
 that doesn't like God telling us what we can't do,

297
00:13:26,460 --> 00:13:29,260
 what we can't say, what we can't have.

298
00:13:29,260 --> 00:13:30,340
 We don't like that.

299
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:32,900
 And so instead of rejoicing and enjoying

300
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:35,820
 all the good things God has given us when we sin,

301
00:13:35,820 --> 00:13:38,160
 we choose to instead enjoy the few things

302
00:13:38,160 --> 00:13:40,300
 that God says, this isn't good for you.

303
00:13:40,300 --> 00:13:42,660
 I don't want this for you, don't have that.

304
00:13:42,660 --> 00:13:44,820
 And we rebel against God just as Adam and Eve did.

305
00:13:44,820 --> 00:13:47,780
 And so my first thing is that we should learn from this.

306
00:13:47,780 --> 00:13:49,500
 The first thing we can gain from this

307
00:13:49,500 --> 00:13:51,920
 is to focus on the good God has given us,

308
00:13:51,920 --> 00:13:54,100
 to overcome the temptation towards the bad

309
00:13:54,100 --> 00:13:55,740
 that is not good for us.

310
00:13:56,620 --> 00:14:01,340
 I'll continue from verse four.

311
00:14:01,340 --> 00:14:02,980
 But the serpent said to the woman,

312
00:14:02,980 --> 00:14:06,020
 you will not surely die, for God knows

313
00:14:06,020 --> 00:14:08,500
 that when you eat of it, your eyes will be opened,

314
00:14:08,500 --> 00:14:12,380
 and you will be like God, knowing good and evil.

315
00:14:12,380 --> 00:14:15,500
 Again, further doubting, now outright denying.

316
00:14:15,500 --> 00:14:18,160
 At first it started with questioning,

317
00:14:18,160 --> 00:14:19,860
 did God really say that?

318
00:14:19,860 --> 00:14:21,480
 To outright denying, that's not true.

319
00:14:21,480 --> 00:14:23,660
 Okay, God said that, but it's not true.

320
00:14:23,660 --> 00:14:27,060
 And I think today we should also be aware of

321
00:14:27,060 --> 00:14:29,880
 and on guard against similar temptations

322
00:14:29,880 --> 00:14:34,760
 to mistrust or outright deny the word of God,

323
00:14:34,760 --> 00:14:37,200
 that he's graciously given us for our good.

324
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:39,820
 So the temptation comes in verse six,

325
00:14:39,820 --> 00:14:43,260
 says that when the woman saw the tree was good for food,

326
00:14:43,260 --> 00:14:45,660
 and that it was a delight to the eyes,

327
00:14:45,660 --> 00:14:48,760
 and that the tree was to be desired to make one wise,

328
00:14:48,760 --> 00:14:50,520
 she took of its fruit and ate,

329
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:54,140
 and she also gave some to her husband who was with her,

330
00:14:54,140 --> 00:14:55,220
 and he ate.

331
00:14:55,220 --> 00:14:57,100
 Then the eyes of both were opened,

332
00:14:57,100 --> 00:14:59,300
 and they knew that they were naked,

333
00:14:59,300 --> 00:15:01,040
 and they sewed fig leaves together

334
00:15:01,040 --> 00:15:03,380
 and made themselves loincloths.

335
00:15:03,380 --> 00:15:07,140
 Adam and Eve had been naked from the beginning.

336
00:15:07,140 --> 00:15:12,060
 Nothing new happened except this loss of innocence,

337
00:15:12,060 --> 00:15:14,100
 where they realized they were naked.

338
00:15:14,100 --> 00:15:15,460
 But the thing with that is that

339
00:15:15,460 --> 00:15:17,100
 there was nothing wrong with nakedness.

340
00:15:17,100 --> 00:15:19,660
 God had made them naked, and it was good.

341
00:15:19,660 --> 00:15:20,940
 But we see what happens here

342
00:15:20,940 --> 00:15:22,800
 when they took and ate of that fruit,

343
00:15:22,800 --> 00:15:25,700
 their morality, their minds, their conscience was corrupted.

344
00:15:25,700 --> 00:15:27,860
 They had lost their sense of innocence.

345
00:15:27,860 --> 00:15:31,640
 And we see that entrance of sin,

346
00:15:31,640 --> 00:15:33,960
 guilt, and shame into the world,

347
00:15:33,960 --> 00:15:36,220
 to the point they tried to cover themselves with leaves,

348
00:15:36,220 --> 00:15:38,180
 which you'll see later in the chapter,

349
00:15:38,180 --> 00:15:40,100
 it was not sufficient.

350
00:15:40,100 --> 00:15:42,500
 That's another sermon that I could,

351
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:44,660
 there's so many sermons you can get from this passage,

352
00:15:44,660 --> 00:15:46,100
 but just remember that.

353
00:15:46,100 --> 00:15:48,920
 They tried to cover themselves, but it wasn't sufficient.

354
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:52,860
 So, verse eight.

355
00:15:52,860 --> 00:15:54,700
 They heard the sound of the Lord God

356
00:15:54,700 --> 00:15:56,980
 walking in the garden in the cool of the day,

357
00:15:56,980 --> 00:15:58,820
 and the man and his wife hid themselves

358
00:15:58,820 --> 00:16:00,700
 from the presence of the Lord God

359
00:16:00,700 --> 00:16:02,340
 among the trees of the garden.

360
00:16:02,340 --> 00:16:04,860
 But the Lord God called to the man and said to him,

361
00:16:04,860 --> 00:16:06,460
 "Where are you?"

362
00:16:06,460 --> 00:16:08,140
 Now, I wanna make a point here

363
00:16:08,140 --> 00:16:10,300
 that when God asked this question,

364
00:16:10,300 --> 00:16:13,140
 he wasn't asking questions the way we ask questions.

365
00:16:13,140 --> 00:16:15,820
 We ask questions because we wanna learn something.

366
00:16:15,820 --> 00:16:17,860
 There's some piece of knowledge we don't have,

367
00:16:17,860 --> 00:16:19,640
 and we want to get it.

368
00:16:19,640 --> 00:16:20,860
 That's not how it works with God.

369
00:16:20,860 --> 00:16:22,940
 God already knows everything.

370
00:16:22,940 --> 00:16:26,520
 There was never a time where God learned something,

371
00:16:26,520 --> 00:16:28,920
 because God already knows everything.

372
00:16:28,920 --> 00:16:31,200
 So, when he asked Adam, "Where are you?"

373
00:16:31,200 --> 00:16:33,960
 It wasn't because he didn't know where Adam was.

374
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:36,920
 It's because he wanted to prick the conscience of Adam,

375
00:16:36,920 --> 00:16:39,600
 so Adam would reflect, "What am I doing?

376
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:40,440
 "Where am I?

377
00:16:40,440 --> 00:16:41,680
 "I'm hiding from God."

378
00:16:41,680 --> 00:16:44,000
 Which doesn't even, how can you hide from the God

379
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:45,520
 who knows all things?

380
00:16:45,520 --> 00:16:48,460
 Whose eyes are everywhere, who sees everything?

381
00:16:48,460 --> 00:16:49,700
 That was the point of this question,

382
00:16:49,700 --> 00:16:51,620
 was to prick Adam's conscience.

383
00:16:51,620 --> 00:16:56,580
 And Adam says this, "I heard the sound of you in the garden,

384
00:16:56,580 --> 00:17:00,940
 "and I was afraid, because I was naked and I hid myself."

385
00:17:00,940 --> 00:17:02,100
 So Adam hid.

386
00:17:02,100 --> 00:17:05,280
 He hid himself from God because of his guilt and shame,

387
00:17:05,280 --> 00:17:06,420
 which we already know.

388
00:17:06,420 --> 00:17:10,980
 I mentioned before, there's no logic in hiding from God.

389
00:17:10,980 --> 00:17:12,780
 But we tend to do the same thing

390
00:17:12,780 --> 00:17:15,060
 in a slightly different way,

391
00:17:15,060 --> 00:17:16,620
 but it's the same thing at the heart of it,

392
00:17:16,620 --> 00:17:20,100
 that when we sin against God and our conscience is pricked,

393
00:17:20,100 --> 00:17:23,000
 we tend to feel that we ought to distance ourselves from God.

394
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:26,520
 Maybe we feel like, "Whatever I did this weekend,

395
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:27,560
 "I know it wasn't right.

396
00:17:27,560 --> 00:17:28,680
 "I shouldn't go to church.

397
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:29,800
 "I can't fellowship.

398
00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:30,620
 "I'm too guilty.

399
00:17:30,620 --> 00:17:33,000
 "I'm not right the way others are right."

400
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:35,320
 Or we feel like, "I can't pray right now.

401
00:17:35,320 --> 00:17:36,220
 "I can't go to God.

402
00:17:36,220 --> 00:17:38,460
 "He's angry with me, 'cause he knows what I just did,

403
00:17:38,460 --> 00:17:39,800
 "what I just said."

404
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:42,180
 Or maybe, "How could I pick up the Bible

405
00:17:42,180 --> 00:17:43,020
 "and read it right now?

406
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:43,840
 "I'm such a hypocrite.

407
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:45,160
 "I just sinned, I can't."

408
00:17:45,160 --> 00:17:48,680
 And so our sin causes us to hide from God in a sense.

409
00:17:48,680 --> 00:17:49,920
 We turn from God.

410
00:17:49,920 --> 00:17:52,300
 Well, on the flip side, how it should be is that

411
00:17:52,300 --> 00:17:54,740
 when we sin, we ought to go to God,

412
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:56,520
 because he's the one who forgives us

413
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:58,880
 and cleanses us and makes us right.

414
00:17:58,880 --> 00:18:01,280
 Sin should not separate us from God

415
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:02,980
 the way it did with Adam and Eve.

416
00:18:02,980 --> 00:18:06,320
 We should go to God, confess our sins,

417
00:18:06,320 --> 00:18:08,740
 and receive forgiveness and restoration.

418
00:18:08,740 --> 00:18:10,480
 We're not gonna find that by hiding from God

419
00:18:10,480 --> 00:18:13,200
 in many of the ways we try to.

420
00:18:13,200 --> 00:18:14,100
 I'm gonna continue.

421
00:18:14,100 --> 00:18:17,800
 Verse 11.

422
00:18:17,800 --> 00:18:20,600
 God said, "Who told you that you were naked?

423
00:18:20,600 --> 00:18:22,800
 "Have you eaten of the tree

424
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:25,720
 "of which I commanded you not to eat?"

425
00:18:25,720 --> 00:18:27,280
 Now, this is an interesting part

426
00:18:27,280 --> 00:18:29,240
 where we see something enter the world

427
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:31,600
 that we're also all still guilty of,

428
00:18:31,600 --> 00:18:32,800
 called the blame game.

429
00:18:32,800 --> 00:18:35,040
 Verse 12.

430
00:18:35,040 --> 00:18:39,440
 "The man said, 'The woman you gave me to be with me.

431
00:18:39,440 --> 00:18:41,440
 "She gave me the fruit of the tree, and I ate.'"

432
00:18:41,480 --> 00:18:44,120
 So Adam not only puts the blame on the woman,

433
00:18:44,120 --> 00:18:45,720
 well, she gave it to me,

434
00:18:45,720 --> 00:18:47,560
 he also kind of puts the blame towards God,

435
00:18:47,560 --> 00:18:50,160
 because it's the woman that you gave me.

436
00:18:50,160 --> 00:18:51,720
 He's already pointing fingers.

437
00:18:51,720 --> 00:18:54,000
 He's already passing the blame.

438
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:56,160
 Then what does the woman say?

439
00:18:56,160 --> 00:18:57,340
 "The Lord God said to the woman,

440
00:18:57,340 --> 00:18:59,400
 "What is this that you have done?"

441
00:18:59,400 --> 00:19:02,440
 The woman said, "The serpent deceived me, and I ate."

442
00:19:02,440 --> 00:19:04,700
 So we already see this lack of accountability

443
00:19:04,700 --> 00:19:06,480
 and responsibility for sin.

444
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:08,720
 Instead of confessing and admitting guilt,

445
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:10,320
 it's, well, it's the woman's fault.

446
00:19:10,320 --> 00:19:11,440
 Oh, it's the serpent's fault.

447
00:19:11,440 --> 00:19:12,360
 Oh, God, it's your fault.

448
00:19:12,360 --> 00:19:13,600
 You put us here.

449
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:16,600
 And we still struggle with that.

450
00:19:16,600 --> 00:19:19,080
 It's difficult to take accountability when we sin.

451
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:22,240
 It's easier to think that, well, it's this person's fault.

452
00:19:22,240 --> 00:19:23,880
 And, you know, no, I wasn't being rude.

453
00:19:23,880 --> 00:19:24,980
 They just took it the wrong way,

454
00:19:24,980 --> 00:19:26,600
 and they shouldn't have started with me.

455
00:19:26,600 --> 00:19:28,480
 You know, we kind of steal all these things

456
00:19:28,480 --> 00:19:32,820
 that Adam and Eve did and stumbled with here.

457
00:19:32,820 --> 00:19:34,800
 They're still stumbling blocks for us today.

458
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:37,640
 We can learn a lot from reading this and from studying it

459
00:19:37,640 --> 00:19:40,580
 and comparing what they did to what we should do.

460
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:42,960
 Okay, but I'll continue.

461
00:19:42,960 --> 00:19:47,860
 The serpent deceived me, and I ate.

462
00:19:47,860 --> 00:19:50,960
 I do want to note that after Adam and Eve sinned,

463
00:19:50,960 --> 00:19:53,980
 it's important to see this, because in this next passage,

464
00:19:53,980 --> 00:19:56,960
 we see the mercy of God, the justice of God,

465
00:19:56,960 --> 00:19:58,320
 but also the mercy of God,

466
00:19:58,320 --> 00:20:01,320
 because Adam and Eve had just been created by God

467
00:20:01,320 --> 00:20:03,840
 from nothing, given everything.

468
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:05,500
 He gave them everything,

469
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:07,800
 and they immediately turned and rebelled

470
00:20:07,800 --> 00:20:10,960
 and committed this heinous, high-handed sin

471
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:14,400
 against Almighty God, against their creator.

472
00:20:14,400 --> 00:20:18,040
 And yet, God first turns to the serpent

473
00:20:18,040 --> 00:20:20,000
 and punishes the serpent,

474
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,260
 not the man and the woman who had sinned against him.

475
00:20:22,260 --> 00:20:24,960
 So even in that, you see some of God's mercy.

476
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:28,160
 God could have just started over from that second

477
00:20:28,160 --> 00:20:31,280
 and created a new earth and a new Adam and a new Eve,

478
00:20:31,280 --> 00:20:32,480
 but he was merciful.

479
00:20:33,360 --> 00:20:36,140
 And the worst of this punishment is on the serpent.

480
00:20:36,140 --> 00:20:39,220
 Verse 14, the Lord God said to the serpent,

481
00:20:39,220 --> 00:20:40,820
 because you have done this,

482
00:20:40,820 --> 00:20:43,500
 cursed are you above all livestock

483
00:20:43,500 --> 00:20:45,540
 and above all beasts of the field.

484
00:20:45,540 --> 00:20:47,060
 On your belly you shall go,

485
00:20:47,060 --> 00:20:50,740
 and dust you shall eat all the days of your life.

486
00:20:50,740 --> 00:20:53,780
 I will put enmity between you and the woman,

487
00:20:53,780 --> 00:20:56,780
 and between your offspring and her offspring.

488
00:20:56,780 --> 00:21:00,820
 He shall bruise your head, and you shall bruise his heel.

489
00:21:01,740 --> 00:21:06,100
 So surely this was the darkest day in human history.

490
00:21:06,100 --> 00:21:09,100
 It was the entrance of sin into the world,

491
00:21:09,100 --> 00:21:11,480
 which at that time was a perfect world,

492
00:21:11,480 --> 00:21:14,140
 an untarnished, unblemished world.

493
00:21:14,140 --> 00:21:15,420
 Paradise was lost.

494
00:21:15,420 --> 00:21:18,820
 We went from perfection to corruption.

495
00:21:18,820 --> 00:21:21,380
 Innocence exchanged for guilt and shame.

496
00:21:21,380 --> 00:21:24,380
 Purity exchanged for sin.

497
00:21:24,380 --> 00:21:26,700
 Hope exchanged for hopelessness.

498
00:21:26,700 --> 00:21:29,700
 Life exchanged for death.

499
00:21:29,700 --> 00:21:31,940
 And even as bleak at times,

500
00:21:31,940 --> 00:21:34,500
 depressing the current state of the world may seem,

501
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:36,780
 when you see all the terrible things happening

502
00:21:36,780 --> 00:21:38,860
 in our city, in our country,

503
00:21:38,860 --> 00:21:40,900
 surely you see it around the globe.

504
00:21:40,900 --> 00:21:42,540
 I can guarantee you,

505
00:21:42,540 --> 00:21:45,600
 nothing we have today is as dark as it was on that day,

506
00:21:45,600 --> 00:21:48,940
 when darkness first entered the world.

507
00:21:48,940 --> 00:21:51,580
 But as is often said,

508
00:21:51,580 --> 00:21:55,060
 it's always darkest before the dawn.

509
00:21:55,060 --> 00:21:58,680
 You see, in the midst of this very darkness,

510
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:02,620
 we find the advent, the emergence of light,

511
00:22:02,620 --> 00:22:04,620
 a dawn of hope,

512
00:22:04,620 --> 00:22:08,380
 a promise given by God himself,

513
00:22:08,380 --> 00:22:12,100
 in which his people have held onto for thousands of years,

514
00:22:12,100 --> 00:22:15,060
 a promise of salvation, redemption,

515
00:22:15,060 --> 00:22:17,940
 restoration, and justice for mankind.

516
00:22:17,940 --> 00:22:22,860
 And we find this promise, ironically, in a curse.

517
00:22:22,860 --> 00:22:26,220
 In verse 15, the Lord God said to the serpent,

518
00:22:26,220 --> 00:22:27,680
 "Because you have done this,

519
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:30,620
 "cursed are you above all livestock

520
00:22:30,620 --> 00:22:32,680
 "and above all beasts of the field.

521
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:33,960
 "On your belly you shall go,

522
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:36,960
 "and dust you shall eat all the days of your life,"

523
00:22:36,960 --> 00:22:39,400
 which is almost a metaphor,

524
00:22:39,400 --> 00:22:43,760
 a picture of utter humiliation, lowliness, defeat.

525
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:48,360
 "I will put enmity," which is conflict, warfare,

526
00:22:48,360 --> 00:22:50,440
 violence, "between you and the woman

527
00:22:50,440 --> 00:22:53,080
 "and between your offspring and her offspring.

528
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:54,480
 "He shall bruise your head,

529
00:22:54,480 --> 00:22:55,960
 "and you shall bruise his heel."

530
00:22:55,960 --> 00:22:58,480
 So this is the curse that God gives to the serpent.

531
00:22:58,480 --> 00:23:01,920
 But even in this curse, we find a promise

532
00:23:01,920 --> 00:23:04,200
 when God says, interestingly,

533
00:23:04,200 --> 00:23:07,200
 "I will put enmity between you and the woman,

534
00:23:07,200 --> 00:23:10,240
 "between your offspring and her offspring.

535
00:23:10,240 --> 00:23:12,440
 "He shall bruise your head."

536
00:23:12,440 --> 00:23:15,320
 There's a pronoun there of an offspring of the woman.

537
00:23:15,320 --> 00:23:18,060
 "He shall bruise your head,

538
00:23:18,060 --> 00:23:19,480
 "and you shall bruise his heel."

539
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:21,960
 And so I wanna talk a little bit about that last part.

540
00:23:21,960 --> 00:23:24,640
 He shall bruise your head, you shall bruise his heel.

541
00:23:24,640 --> 00:23:28,440
 It's referring to the offspring or the seed of the woman.

542
00:23:28,440 --> 00:23:30,320
 In Hebrew, this is the word zara.

543
00:23:30,320 --> 00:23:33,760
 Its meaning is like an offspring, a descendant,

544
00:23:33,760 --> 00:23:35,600
 a child, a literal seed.

545
00:23:35,600 --> 00:23:39,080
 And in the Bible, when we see this word used in this way,

546
00:23:39,080 --> 00:23:42,600
 it always refers to a man, the seed of Abraham,

547
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:44,320
 the seed of David.

548
00:23:44,320 --> 00:23:45,480
 But in this one instance,

549
00:23:45,480 --> 00:23:48,000
 of all the places I could find in the Bible,

550
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:51,160
 the seed describes a woman.

551
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:54,080
 And this is because the seed is in,

552
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:55,440
 and it comes from the man.

553
00:23:55,440 --> 00:23:56,960
 It doesn't come from the woman.

554
00:23:56,960 --> 00:23:58,800
 So it's curious that God would talk

555
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:00,760
 about the seed of a woman.

556
00:24:00,760 --> 00:24:02,920
 This wouldn't really make sense normally,

557
00:24:02,920 --> 00:24:05,440
 but I think this is significant.

558
00:24:05,440 --> 00:24:06,600
 Because in this promise,

559
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:10,200
 the seed of the woman is referring to a certain someone.

560
00:24:10,200 --> 00:24:12,280
 And if you can think of who it is,

561
00:24:12,280 --> 00:24:13,840
 go ahead and just shout it out.

562
00:24:13,840 --> 00:24:16,480
 Exactly, exactly.

563
00:24:16,480 --> 00:24:18,880
 'Cause there's one person, one child,

564
00:24:18,880 --> 00:24:20,600
 in all of human history,

565
00:24:20,600 --> 00:24:23,320
 who was born without a human father.

566
00:24:23,320 --> 00:24:26,240
 So literally, Jesus, the Messiah,

567
00:24:26,240 --> 00:24:27,440
 born of the Virgin Mary,

568
00:24:27,440 --> 00:24:31,960
 could only be the seed of a woman.

569
00:24:31,960 --> 00:24:34,460
 Jesus Christ, the Son of God,

570
00:24:34,460 --> 00:24:37,040
 the seed of the woman,

571
00:24:37,040 --> 00:24:39,440
 promised by God from the very beginning

572
00:24:39,440 --> 00:24:41,240
 that he would be the one to bruise,

573
00:24:41,240 --> 00:24:44,520
 to crush the head of the serpent.

574
00:24:44,520 --> 00:24:47,800
 God says, "He will bruise your head,

575
00:24:47,800 --> 00:24:49,160
 "you will bruise his heel."

576
00:24:49,160 --> 00:24:50,720
 And so you can compare the two.

577
00:24:50,720 --> 00:24:52,720
 To bruise someone's heel,

578
00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:54,280
 it's like a snake bite to the back.

579
00:24:54,280 --> 00:24:55,520
 You don't see it coming.

580
00:24:55,520 --> 00:24:58,920
 It's kind of an underhanded, deceptive attack.

581
00:24:58,920 --> 00:25:00,720
 But if a serpent were to come on the stage,

582
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:03,380
 and I don't know if we have snakes in Chicago.

583
00:25:03,380 --> 00:25:04,320
 I know we have rats.

584
00:25:04,320 --> 00:25:07,120
 Maybe if we had some more snakes, we'd have less rats.

585
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:09,900
 But if a snake came on stage and bit me in the heel,

586
00:25:09,900 --> 00:25:12,360
 it would hurt, it would not be great,

587
00:25:12,360 --> 00:25:13,880
 but it wouldn't kill me.

588
00:25:13,880 --> 00:25:15,440
 It's not a fatal blow.

589
00:25:15,440 --> 00:25:19,840
 But if I turned around and stomped on that snake's head,

590
00:25:19,840 --> 00:25:20,760
 that's it.

591
00:25:20,760 --> 00:25:21,680
 It's a fatal blow.

592
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:23,080
 It's a death strike.

593
00:25:23,080 --> 00:25:24,800
 A complete defeat for that snake.

594
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:27,800
 And so in that curse, there's also a promise

595
00:25:27,800 --> 00:25:32,600
 that this one figure, this male offspring of the woman,

596
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:35,360
 this savior, would be bruised on the heel,

597
00:25:35,360 --> 00:25:37,700
 would suffer some temporary defeat.

598
00:25:37,700 --> 00:25:42,360
 But in that defeat, he would ultimately defeat the serpent.

599
00:25:42,360 --> 00:25:44,680
 And so this passage right here is known

600
00:25:44,680 --> 00:25:48,960
 as the Proto-Evangelium, which just means the first gospel.

601
00:25:48,960 --> 00:25:52,400
 It is the first gospel message in all of the Bible.

602
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:55,920
 The first glimpse of hope, promise of redemption,

603
00:25:55,920 --> 00:25:59,360
 fulfilled in Jesus Christ's death and resurrection.

604
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:03,120
 Because in death, Jesus was rejected and scorned

605
00:26:03,120 --> 00:26:06,580
 by his own people, betrayed by them.

606
00:26:06,580 --> 00:26:10,400
 Betrayed even by a disciple who he loved as a brother.

607
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:12,520
 On the way to the cross, he was abandoned

608
00:26:12,520 --> 00:26:14,340
 by the rest of his disciples.

609
00:26:14,340 --> 00:26:18,520
 In that crucifixion, in that rejection and abandonment,

610
00:26:18,520 --> 00:26:22,440
 Jesus suffered the serpent's bite to the heel.

611
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:25,920
 Yet in his resurrection, he crushed the head of the serpent

612
00:26:25,920 --> 00:26:30,480
 declaring victory over sin, death, and the grave.

613
00:26:30,480 --> 00:26:34,200
 And so this was the hope, this savior figure to come,

614
00:26:34,200 --> 00:26:37,120
 was the hope of Adam and Eve, that one of their descendants

615
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:39,560
 would one day crush the head of the serpent.

616
00:26:39,560 --> 00:26:42,320
 That this figure, this messiah, the savior,

617
00:26:42,320 --> 00:26:44,740
 would defeat Satan and rid humanity

618
00:26:44,740 --> 00:26:47,200
 of his evil schemes once and for all.

619
00:26:47,200 --> 00:26:49,900
 It is this savior who is the messiah of Israel,

620
00:26:49,900 --> 00:26:51,920
 the one in which the people of Israel

621
00:26:51,920 --> 00:26:53,760
 hoped in for thousands of years.

622
00:26:53,760 --> 00:26:58,920
 The one whose birth we celebrate every year at Christmas.

623
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:02,000
 He is the one upon which all of our hopes rest.

624
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:05,640
 All of God's people rest their hope in this one savior.

625
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:07,960
 He is the solution to all of our problems.

626
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:10,360
 The ones that, the sin problem that has plagued

627
00:27:10,360 --> 00:27:14,220
 all of mankind throughout history and plagues us today.

628
00:27:14,220 --> 00:27:18,020
 Our problem is sin, it's devastating effects on our bodies,

629
00:27:18,020 --> 00:27:22,780
 our families, every aspect of our life is marred by sin.

630
00:27:22,780 --> 00:27:27,460
 But just as it is written, she will give birth to a son

631
00:27:27,460 --> 00:27:30,020
 and you shall call his name Jesus.

632
00:27:30,020 --> 00:27:34,300
 For he will save his people from their sins.

633
00:27:34,300 --> 00:27:36,940
 This is the hope that we must cling on to.

634
00:27:36,940 --> 00:27:40,000
 The same hope that Adam and Eve, even after the fall,

635
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:43,380
 even after such a devastating loss of perfection,

636
00:27:43,380 --> 00:27:45,140
 this was the hope they held to.

637
00:27:45,140 --> 00:27:47,380
 The same hope we see throughout the scriptures.

638
00:27:47,380 --> 00:27:50,420
 So many of God's faithful held on to this hope

639
00:27:50,420 --> 00:27:53,140
 of a savior, of a redeemer.

640
00:27:53,140 --> 00:27:56,200
 One example I wanna look at from the book of Job.

641
00:27:56,200 --> 00:28:00,260
 A great example, Job was a man who lost nearly everything,

642
00:28:00,260 --> 00:28:03,760
 who by worldly standards had nothing to live for.

643
00:28:03,760 --> 00:28:07,100
 His possessions, gone, his children, dead,

644
00:28:07,100 --> 00:28:10,940
 his own friends accused him of evil.

645
00:28:10,940 --> 00:28:12,500
 His wife even asked him, you know,

646
00:28:12,500 --> 00:28:16,300
 why don't you just curse God and die already?

647
00:28:16,300 --> 00:28:18,860
 Yet in spite of all his suffering and anguish,

648
00:28:18,860 --> 00:28:21,180
 Job could confidently declare this.

649
00:28:21,180 --> 00:28:24,780
 I know that my redeemer lives and that in the end,

650
00:28:24,780 --> 00:28:27,460
 he will stand on the earth.

651
00:28:27,460 --> 00:28:29,920
 And after my skin has been destroyed,

652
00:28:29,920 --> 00:28:32,620
 yet in my flesh, I will see God.

653
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:34,820
 I myself will see him with my own eyes,

654
00:28:34,820 --> 00:28:38,740
 I and not another, how my heart yearns within me.

655
00:28:38,740 --> 00:28:40,860
 You see, despite Job's sorrow and suffering,

656
00:28:40,860 --> 00:28:45,820
 he was able to hold on to hope in God, his redeemer.

657
00:28:45,820 --> 00:28:48,980
 And so I ask, can you, can we say with Job,

658
00:28:48,980 --> 00:28:53,020
 I know my redeemer lives in the midst of our suffering,

659
00:28:53,020 --> 00:28:55,140
 my redeemer lives.

660
00:28:55,140 --> 00:28:57,460
 In the midst of frustration, difficulty,

661
00:28:57,460 --> 00:28:59,740
 disappointment with family, with friends,

